\begin_layout Description
Partition A partition is a portion of a drive which stores data (files)
 using a certain format named file system.
 It may be part of an operating system installation, or simply be used for
 storing files.
 A drive may be split into multiple partitions, each acting as its own separate
 entity and using its own file system.
 All drives, be they hard drives or flash drives such as USB keys, contain
 one or more partitions.
 An example of a partition is the famous C: drive used by Microsoft Windows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
File
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

system A file system is a format used to write files in a partition.
 Some popular file systems are 
\series bold
ntfs
\series default
 (used by Microsoft Windows), 
\series bold
ext4
\series default
 (used by Linux), 
\series bold
fat32
\series default
, 
\series bold
btrfs
\series default
 and 
\series bold
xfs
\series default
.
 Each one is used in a different context and has its own strengths and weaknesse
s.
 For instance, fat32 can be read by about any operating system, but each
 file stored must be smaller than 4 GB.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Partition
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

table A partition table is a list of all the partitions existing on a drive.
 The two main types are 
\series bold
Master Boot Record
\series default
 (MBR) and 
\series bold
GUID Partition Table
\series default
 (GPT).
 Different partition tables allow for different types of partitions on them,
 such as primary and extended.
 MBR partition tables are generally used on older BIOS systems and can only
 contain a limited number of primary partitions, while GPT is generally
 used on newer UEFI systems and do not have such a restriction.
 This is not always the case though.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Directory A directory is what is often called a folder on Windows.
 You can treat them as one and the same.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Directory
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Tree The directories on Linux are arranged in the form of a tree, originating
 from the / directory, called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

root
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 directory.
 Each one has a specific use.
 For example, the /home directory stores the users' personal files, while
 the /etc directory stores system-wide configuration files.
 A complete description of the directory tree can be found on Wikipedia:
 
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Filesystem_Hierarchy_Standard
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Mount
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

point A mount point represents the directory from which a partition is accessibl
e.
 Just like clicking on the C: drive in your file manager on Windows allows
 you to see the contents of this partition, clicking on a directory where
 a partition is mounted will allow you to view its contents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover, several programs are used when booting your computer, from starting
 the hardware to logging in the operating system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Live-CD A Live-CD is a version of an operating system that runs in the computer'
s memory, without needing to access the hard drive.
 It is generally loaded from a CD, DVD or USB key that was used at boot.
 Changes made to the Live environment are not saved.
 Live-CDs are often used to give a preview of an operating system and include
 tools to install it.
 They can also be used to manage the hard drive's partitions and rescue
 lost data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
BIOS The 
\series bold
Basic Input/Output System
\series default
 (BIOS) is a firmware used when booting to initialize hardware.
 It offers various settings in menus accessible when pressing a specific
 key during boot.
 Systems using BIOS often have a MBR partition table.
 It can be used to boot on a USB stick, start a Live environment and install
 Manjaro.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
UEFI The 
\series bold
Unified Extensible Firmware Interface
\series default
 (UEFI) is the successor of the BIOS.
 It is often used on newer computers.
 It still has BIOS-like menus and often has a legacy mode, which uses BIOS.
 The partition scheme used by operating systems on a computer using UEFI
 is slightly different from the one used on a BIOS system.
 For instance, a small fat32 partition is needed to contain some files used
 when booting.
 Systems using UEFI often have a GPT partition table.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Boot
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

loader A boot loader is a program which enables you to choose which operating
 system to boot when you turn on your computer.
 At boot, a list of all detected operating systems on the computer is displayed.
 One of the most widely used boot loaders is 
\series bold
GRUB
\series default
.
 It is the one installed by Calamares, the installer used by Manjaro.
\end_layout

